<DOC><DOCNO> AP880425-0225 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-25-88 0727EDT</FILEID><FIRST>a a BC-History Adv01   04-25 0488</FIRST><SECOND>BC-History, Adv01,0512</SECOND><NOTE>$adv01</NOTE><NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 1</NOTE><HEAD>Today in History</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Today is Sunday, May 1, the 122nd day of 1988. There are 244days left in the year.   Today's Highlight in History:   On May 1, 1960, the Soviet Union shot down an American U-2reconnaissance plane near Sverdlovsk and captured its pilot,Francis Gary Powers. Imprisoned for espionage, Powers was releasedby the Soviets in 1962 in exchange for a Soviet spy captured by theU.S.   On this date:   In 1786, Mozart's opera ``The Marriage of Figaro'' premiered inVienna.   In 1884, construction began on the first ``skyscraper,'' a10-story structure in Chicago built by the Home Insurance Co. ofNew York.   In 1898, Commodore George Dewey gave the famous command, ``Youmay fire when you are ready, Gridley,'' as an American naval forcedestroyed a Spanish fleet in Manila Bay.   In 1931, New York's 102-story Empire State Building wasdedicated.   In 1931, singer Kate Smith began her long-running radio programon CBS.   In 1941, the motion picture ``Citizen Kane,'' directed by andstarring Orson Welles, premiered in New York.   In 1948, the People's Democratic Republic of Korea (North Korea)was proclaimed.   In 1963, James W. Whittaker of Redmond, Wash., became the firstAmerican to conquer Mount Everest as he and a Sherpa guide reachedthe summit.   In 1967, Anastasio Somoza Debayle became president of Nicaragua.   In 1967, the novel ``The Fixer'' by Bernard Malamud and the play``A Delicate Balance'' by Edward Albee won Pulitzer Prizes.   In 1967, entertainer Elvis Presley married Priscilla Beaulieu inLas Vegas, Nev. (They divorced in 1973.)   In 1971, Amtrak began operations, taking over passenger servicefrom the nation's railroads.   In 1981, Sen. Harrison A. Williams Jr. (D-N.J.) was convicted ofbribery-conspiracy charges stemming from the FBI's ABSCAMinvestigation.   In 1982, the World's Fair opened in Knoxville, Tenn.   Ten years ago: President Jimmy Carter and Israeli Prime MinisterMenachem Begin celebrated the 30th anniversary of the founding ofIsrael at a White House reception. Ernest Morial was inaugurated asthe first black mayor of the city of New Orleans.   Five years ago: President Reagan paid his first visit to theVietnam Veterans Memorial, placing a bouquet of yellow and pinkflowers in the gap between the monument's granite walls.   One year ago: During his visit to West Germany, Pope John PaulII beatified Edith Stein, a Jewish-born Carmelite nun who wasgassed in the Nazi death camp at Auschwitz during the Holocaust.   Today's Birthdays: Actor Glenn Ford is 72. Actor John Beradinois 71. TV personality Jack Parr is 70. Actor Dan O'Herlihy is 69.Author Joseph Heller is 65. Former astronaut Scott Carpenter is 63.Singer Judy Collins is 49. Singer Rita Coolidge is 43.Singer-songwriter Ray Parker Jr. is 34. Jockey Steve Cauthen is 28.   Thought for Today: ``The tragedy of love is indifference.'' _ W.Somerset Maugham, English author (1874-1965).</TEXT><NOTE>End Adv</NOTE></DOC>